&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;slide transition&lt;/strong&gt; is the effect that occurs &lt;strong&gt;when one slide replaces another&lt;/strong&gt; during a slideshow presentation in Microsoft PowerPoint.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This can include fading in and out, sliding in from one side, and various other visual changes.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Animation:&lt;/strong&gt; This is used to add motion to objects (such as text, shapes, pictures etc.) within a slide. There are several types of animations, like entrance, emphasis, exit, and motion paths.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Custom Animation: &lt;/strong&gt;This refers to the ability to create your own animation sequence within a slide. With custom animation, you can determine the order of animated objects, the duration, and the way the animation is triggered (for example, by a click or automatically).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Preset Animation:&lt;/strong&gt; These are predefined animation sequences that PowerPoint provides for convenience. For example, you can choose a preset to make text fly in from the right, or to make an image grow and spin at the same time.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Track&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In &lt;strong&gt;magnetic disks&lt;/strong&gt;, data is organized in concentric circular paths known as &lt;strong&gt;tracks&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A track is a circular division of the disk surface, and it is used to store and retrieve data efficiently.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Each &lt;strong&gt;track&lt;/strong&gt; is further divided into smaller units called &lt;strong&gt;sectors&lt;/strong&gt;, which are the actual storage locations for data.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The tracks are created during the disk formatting process to ensure proper organization of data.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Tracks allow the &lt;strong&gt;read/write head&lt;/strong&gt; of the disk to locate and access data stored on the platter.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Tracks are numbered sequentially from the outer edge of the disk to the inner edge, enabling systematic storage.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This organization aids in optimizing the &lt;strong&gt;performance of the disk&lt;/strong&gt; and ensures that data can be accessed quickly.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The concept of tracks is fundamental to the working of &lt;strong&gt;hard disk drives (HDDs)&lt;/strong&gt; and other storage devices based on magnetic media.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sector&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;sector&lt;/strong&gt; is the smallest unit of data storage on a magnetic disk.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a subdivision of a track and typically holds a fixed amount of data, such as &lt;strong&gt;512 bytes or 4 KB&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Sectors are used to store individual data blocks and are accessed by the disk&amp;#39;s &lt;strong&gt;read/write head&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Head&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;head&lt;/strong&gt; refers to the mechanism in a magnetic disk that reads and writes data on the disk platter.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;There is usually one head per platter surface in a hard disk drive.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The head uses magnetic signals to interact with the data stored on the disk.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Block&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;block&lt;/strong&gt; is a unit of data that is transferred between the disk and the computer&amp;#39;s memory.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It consists of multiple sectors grouped together, and its size can vary depending on the &lt;strong&gt;file system&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Blocks are crucial for efficient data storage and retrieval in modern storage devices.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Perl.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;LISP and PROLOG are two of the oldest programming languages that were designed specifically for artificial intelligence (AI).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are still used for some AI applications, but they have been mostly replaced by Python.&lt;/li&gt;
