&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A barcode is an optical, machine-readable, representation of data.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The data usually describes something about the object that carries the barcode.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Originally barcodes systematically represented data by varying the widths and spacings of parallel lines, and may be referred to as linear or one-dimensional (1D).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Later two-dimensional (2D) codes were developed, using rectangles, dots, hexagons and other geometric patterns in two dimensions, usually called barcodes although they do not use bars as such.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Barcodes originally were scanned by special optical scanners called barcode readers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Later applications software became available for devices that could read images, such as smartphones with cameras.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

